ce:section.ce:para:
H. pylori was chosen as a model pathogen to evaluate the potential of the developed FCD-Ab-GO FRET immunosensor for the quantitative detection of whole cell bacteria. The results of fluorescence recovery study in PBS solution with gradient concentration of H. pylori (0-107 cells mL−1) under optimized conditions and the corresponding dose-response curve are shown in Fig. 3
a and (b) respectively. All the fluorescence measurements were carried out upon incubation of serially diluted (10-fold) deactivated bacteria with prefixed optimized FCD-Ab-GO complex. Fig. 3a revealed that with increasing concentration of H. pylori, fluorescence emission at 412 nm increases gradually and accordingly. The fluorescence is primarily from FCD-Ab-Pylori assembly which is formed upon addition of pathogen into the mixture of FCD-Ab-GO complex due to the specific affinity and binding of Ab towards outer membrane protein of H. pylori. TEM study (Fig. 3d) supports the successful binding of FCDs on the surface of H. pylori further confirming the formation of FCD-Ab-Pylori assembly prerequisite for restoration of the fluorescence signal. Moreover, as the concentration of bacteria increases, FCD-Ab-Pylori assembly are formed in larger extent and subsequently liberated from the surface of GO and leads to the gradual restoration of the fluorescence signal. A dose-response curve is constructed by plotting the restored fluorescence intensity as a function of logarithm of bacterial concentration as shown in Fig. 3b. The linear equation is expressed as y = 85x + 65.42 with a strong correlation coefficient (R2) of 0.98 and the limit of detection (LOD) was estimated to be 10 cells mL−1 as per 3δ/S criterion where δ stands for the standard deviation for negative control (n = 6) and S is the slope of the plot with an analytical detection range of 0-107 cells mL−1. It is clearly seen from Fig. 3c that when pathogen concentration is 5 cells mL−1, the fluorescence intensity is non-significant (p = 0.8 i.e. >0.05) however, the corresponding intensity for 10 cells mL−1 is higher than that of 5 cells mL−1 and the negative control (p = 0.0062, <0.01) validating 10 cells mL−1 as LOD. It is also observed that at higher pathogen concentration (100 cells mL−1 and onwards) the p = 0.0001 which is highly significant. Therefore, the current approach provides the higher sensitivity for the detection of whole cell H. pylori as compared to previously reported studies (Table 1
) without using expensive instruments [3] and complicated organic-inorganic hybrid system [35]. Furthermore, the developed FRET immunosensor is cost effective, fast and sensitive for H. pylori monitoring.
